# Distributed rate limiting

- Use a shared store (Redis) for counters — in-memory limits fail with multiple instances.
- Prefer atomic increment (Redis INCR + EXPIRE) or Lua scripts for accuracy.
- Partition limits by tenant/user/key to prevent one abuser affecting all users.
- Implement global + per-tenant limits (defense in depth).
- Handle Redis failures: fail open for non-critical paths, fail closed for costly operations.
- Sync clock skew is less critical with sliding window in Redis sorted sets.
- Consider leaky bucket at gateway + token bucket at service level for layered protection.
- Propagate rate limit context in service mesh headers when using microservices.
- Monitor false positive rate (legitimate users hitting limits).
- Document limit tiers in API docs so clients can implement backoff.
